# Sprinkler Network (classic 4-variable BN)
# Structure: Cloudy -> {Sprinkler, Rain}; {Sprinkler, Rain} -> WetGrass
# Demonstrates converging connections and explaining patterns of conditional independence:
#   - Sprinkler âŸ‚ Rain | Cloudy
#   - Sprinkler and Rain become (slightly) dependent when conditioning on WetGrass (a collider)
# Probabilities from the widely-used example (rounded to typical textbook values):
# P(Cloudy) = 0.5
# P(Sprinkler=1 | Cloudy=1) = 0.1 ; P(Sprinkler=1 | Cloudy=0) = 0.5
# P(Rain=1 | Cloudy=1) = 0.8 ; P(Rain=1 | Cloudy=0) = 0.2
# P(WetGrass=1 | Sprinkler, Rain):
#   S R : P(W=1)
#   1 1 : 0.99
#   1 0 : 0.90
#   0 1 : 0.90
#   0 0 : 0.00
# File format:
#   variables: in topological order
#   For each variable: either "Var : None" with prior, or "Var: Parents" with CPT entries.

variables: Cloudy, Sprinkler, Rain, WetGrass

Cloudy: None
1: 0.5  # P(Cloudy=1)

Sprinkler: Cloudy
1: 0.1   # P(S=1|C=1)
0: 0.5   # P(S=1|C=0)

Rain: Cloudy
1: 0.8   # P(R=1|C=1)
0: 0.2   # P(R=1|C=0)

WetGrass: Sprinkler, Rain
11: 0.99  # P(W=1|S=1,R=1)
10: 0.90  # P(W=1|S=1,R=0)
01: 0.90  # P(W=1|S=0,R=1)
00: 0.00  # P(W=1|S=0,R=0)
